{"title_page": "Solar power in India", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=February 2013}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=December 2012}}\n[[File:India GHI mid-size-map 156x194mm-300dpi v20191015.png|thumb|Solar potential of India]]\n'''Solar power in India''' is a fast developing industry. The country's solar installed capacity reached 34.404 GW as of 29 February 2020.<ref name=ach>{{cite news|title=Physical Progress (Achievements)|url=https://mnre.gov.in/the-ministry/physical-progress|accessdate=18 July 2019|publisher=Ministry of New & Renewable Energy}}</ref> India has the lowest capital cost per MW globally to install [[solar power]] plants.<ref>{{cite news|title=India becomes lowest-cost producer of solar power |url=https://energy.economictimes.indiatimes.com/news/renewable/india-becomes-lowest-cost-producer-of-solar-power/69565769|accessdate=1 June 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|title=Race Heats Up For Title Of Cheapest Solar Energy In The World|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/dominicdudley/2019/10/17/cheapest-solar-energy-in-the-world/#517f472a4772|accessdate=28 October 2019}}</ref>    \n\nThe Indian government had an initial target of 20 GW capacity for 2022, which was achieved four years ahead of schedule.<ref name=\"bsInJan2018\" /><ref name=\"ToiOnSolarJan2018\" /><ref>{{Cite journal | doi=10.1007/s40032-018-0454-6|title = Solar Energy a Path to India's Prosperity| journal=Journal of the Institution of Engineers (India): Series C|volume = 100|issue = 3|pages = 539\u2013546|year = 2018|last1 = Chandra|first1 = Yogender Pal| last2=Singh| first2=Arashdeep| last3=Kannojiya| first3=Vikas| last4=Kesari| first4=J. P.}}</ref> In 2015 the target was raised to 100 GW of solar capacity (including 40 GW from [[rooftop solar]]) by 2022, targeting an investment of {{USD}}100 billion.<ref>[http://www.business-standard.com/article/news-ians/government-looking-at-100-000-mw-solar-power-by-2022-114111701373_1.html Government looking at 100,000 MW solar power by 2022]</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.reuters.com/article/2015/01/02/india-solar-idUSL3N0UG13H20150102 |title=India's Modi raises solar investment target to $100 bln by 2022 |date=2015-01-02 |publisher=Reuters |author=Krishna N. Das |accessdate=2015-01-02}}</ref><ref name=\":1\">{{cite web |url=http://www.pv-tech.org/news/india_releases_individual_state_targets_for_40gw_rooftop_solar_by_2022 |title=India releases state targets for 40GW rooftop solar by 2022 |access-date=2016-07-29}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://mnre.gov.in/file-manager/UserFiles/Tentative-State-wise-break-up-of-Renewable-Power-by-2022.pdf |title=State-wise break-up of solar power target by the year 2022 |access-date=11 August 2016}}</ref><ref name=\"renewableET201607182\">{{Cite news |url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/industry/energy/power/government-working-to-double-generation-target-from-solar-parks/articleshow/53268569.cms |title=Government working to double generation target from solar parks |date=2016-07-18 |publisher=Economic Times |format= |accessdate=2016-07-18|newspaper=The Economic Times }}</ref> India has established nearly 42 solar parks to make land available to the promoters of solar plants.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://mnre.gov.in/sites/default/files/uploads/18.%20List%20of%20Solar%20Parks%20as%20on%2031-05-2019.docx |title=List of solar parks in India |accessdate=7 September 2019}}</ref>\n\nIndia expanded its solar-generation capacity 8 times from 2,650 MW on 26 May 2014 to over 20 GW as on 31 January 2018.<ref name=\"bsInJan2018\">{{cite web | url=http://www.businesstoday.in/current/economy-politics/india-achieves-20-gw-solar-capacity-goal-4-years-ahead-deadline/story/269266.html |title=Achieving 2022 target four years ahead of schedule |accessdate=2018-02-04}}</ref><ref name=\"ToiOnSolarJan2018\">{{cite web|url=https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/home/environment/developmental-issues/india-hits-20gw-solar-capacity-milestone/articleshow/62715512.cms|title=India hits 20 GW solar capacity milestone|accessdate=4 February 2018}}</ref> \nThe country added 3 GW of solar capacity in 2015\u20132016, 5 GW in 2016\u20132017 and over 10 GW in 2017\u20132018, with the average current price of solar electricity dropping to 18% below the average price of its coal-fired counterpart.<ref name=pg>{{cite news |title=India's solar capacity to cross 20GW in next 15 months: Piyush Goyal |url=http://economictimes.indiatimes.com/industry/energy/power/indias-solar-energy-capacity-expanded-by-record-5525-mw/articleshow/58037873.cms |website=Economic Times |accessdate=2017-04-06}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.livemint.com/Industry/dUQtwINipgqq4xT0feuxqJ/USs-Paris-climate-deal-exit-may-lower-Indias-solar-power-t.html |title=US's Paris climate deal exit may lower India's solar power tariffs further |accessdate=2017-06-16 }}</ref><ref name=\"bbcParisClimateDeal\">{{cite news |url=https://www.bbc.com/news/science-environment-40120770 |title=Five effects of a US pull-out from Paris climate deal |last=McGrath |first=Matt |publisher=BBC |date=2017-06-01 |accessdate=2017-06-01 |format= }}</ref>. By the end of September 2019, India has installed more than 82,580 MW of renewable energy capacity with around 31,150 MW of capacity under various stages of installation.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://pib.gov.in/newsite/pmreleases.aspx?mincode=28|title=PIB|website=pib.gov.in|access-date=2019-10-30}}</ref>\n\nRooftop solar power accounts for 2.1 GW, of which 70% is industrial or commercial.<ref name=srtgw1>{{cite news|url=https://www.downtoearth.org.in/news/energy/renewable-energy-in-india-why-rooftop-remains-the-most-untapped-solar-source-62873|title= Renewable energy in India: why rooftop remains the most untapped solar source|accessdate=18 January 2019}}</ref> \nIn addition to its large-scale grid-connected solar photovoltaic (PV) initiative, India is developing off-grid solar power for local energy needs.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://economictimes.indiatimes.com/industry/energy/power/solar-water-pumps-can-help-india-surpass-100-gw-target-report/articleshow/65214158.cms|title=Solar water pumps can help India surpass 100 GW target: Report |accessdate= 2 August 2017}}</ref> \nSolar products have increasingly helped to meet rural needs; by the end of 2015 just under one million [[solar lantern]]s were sold in the country, reducing the need for kerosene.<ref name=\":0\">{{cite web |url=http://mnre.gov.in/file-manager/annual-report/2015-2016/EN/Chapter%201/chapter_1.htm |title=Ministry of New and Renewable Energy, Annual Report 2015-2016 |date= |website= |publisher= |access-date=2017-04-21}}</ref> \nThat year, 118,700 solar home lighting systems were installed and 46,655 solar street lighting installations were provided under a national program;<ref name=\":0\" /> just over 1.4 million [[solar cooker]]s were distributed in India.<ref name=\":0\" />\n\nThe [[International Solar Alliance]] (ISA), proposed by India as a founder member, is headquartered in India.\n\n==National solar potential==\n{{anchor|Solar resources}}\nWith about 300 clear and sunny days in a year, the calculated [[solar energy]] incidence on India's land area is about 5000 trillion [[kilowatt-hour]]s (kWh) per year (or 5 [[Exa-|E]]Wh/yr).<ref name=\"SPSEPRIE\">{{cite journal |last1=Muneer |first1=T. |last2=Asif |first2=M. |last3=Munawwar |first3=S. |doi=10.1016/j.rser.2004.03.004 |title=Sustainable production of solar electricity with particular reference to the Indian economy |journal=Renewable and Sustainable Energy Reviews |volume=9 |issue=5 |pages=444 |year=2005 |pmid= |pmc=}} (publication archived in ScienceDirect, needs subscription or access via university)</ref><ref name=\"mnreSolar\">{{cite web |url=http://www.mnre.gov.in/schemes/grid-connected/solar/ |title=Solar |publisher=Ministry of New and Renewable Energy, Govt. of India |accessdate=2014-02-21 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140225160014/http://www.mnre.gov.in/schemes/grid-connected/solar/ |archive-date=25 February 2014 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> The solar energy available in a single year exceeds the possible energy output of all of the [[fossil fuel]] energy reserves in India. The daily average solar-power-plant generation capacity in India is 0.20 kWh per m<sup>2</sup> of used land area, equivalent to 1400\u20131800 peak (rated) capacity operating hours in a year with available, commercially-proven technology.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://photovoltaic-software.com/PV-solar-energy-calculation.php  |title=How to calculate the annual solar energy output of a photovoltaic system? |accessdate=2017-06-30}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.pveducation.org/pvcdrom/modules/mismatch-effects  |title=Comprehensive technical data of PV modules |accessdate=2015-02-21}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://mercomindia.com/mono-perc-modules-india/  |title=Mono PERC Solar Modules are Coming to India; It is Just a Matter of When |accessdate=23 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Installations by region==\n\n===Installated cumulative national and state-wise capacity===\n\n{{Bar graph\n| title       = Installed solar PV on 31 March<ref name=year>{{cite web|url=https://mnre.gov.in/img/documents/uploads/0ce0bba7b9f24b32aed4d89265d6b067.pdf|title= Page 15, Solar power - Overview |accessdate=16 March 2020}}</ref>\n| float       = right\n| bar_width   = 24\n| width_units = em\n| data_max    = 30000\n| label_type  = Year\n| data_type   = Cumulative Capacity (in MW)\n| label1      = 2010\n| data1       = 161\n| label2      = 2011\n| data2       = 461\n| label3      = 2012\n| data3       = 1205\n| label4      = 2013\n| data4       = 2319\n| label5      = 2014\n| data5       = 2632\n| label6      = 2015\n| data6       = 3744\n| label7      = 2016\n| data7       = 6763\n| label8      = 2017\n| data8       = 12289\n| label9      = 2018\n| data9       = 21,651\n| label10      = 2019\n| data10       = 28,181\n}}\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" style=\"text-align: right;\"\n|+ Ground mounted 