o grow to 40 GW by 2022 under national targets.<ref name=\":1\" /> A rough calculation would imply that India had around just 430 MW of residential rooftop solar, whilst the [[Solar power in the United Kingdom|UK]] with around half the overall solar capacity of India had over 2,500 MW of residential solar in 2018. The smallest segment was off-grid solar at 919 MW which could help play a role in reaching villages and dwellings without access to the national grid.\n\n=={{anchor|List of major photovoltaic power stations}}Major photovoltaic power stations==\n{{See also|List of photovoltaic power stations|List of power stations in India#Solar}}\nBelow is a list of solar power generation facilities with a capacity of at least 10 MW.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.cea.nic.in/reports/others/planning/rpm/Plant-wise%20details%20of%20RE%20Installed%20Capacity-merged.pdf|title=Plant wise details of Renewable Energy Installed Capacity|accessdate=21 March 2020}}</ref> \n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\"\n|+ Major photovoltaic (PV) power plants\n|-\n! Plant !! State \n!Coordinates!! DC peak power (MW) !! Commissioned\n!Notes\n!Ref\n|-\n|[[Bhadla Solar Park]]\n|[[Rajasthan]]\n|{{small|{{coord|27|32|22.81|N|71|54|54.91|E|name=Bhadla Solar Park}}}}\n|2245\n|March 2020\n|Biggest solar park in the world as on March 2020\n|<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://www.ndtv.com/india-news/countrys-biggest-solar-park-at-the-heart-of-indias-clean-energy-push-1696271|title=Country's Biggest Solar Park In Rajasthan, At The Heart Of India's Clean Energy Push|work=NDTV.com|access-date=2017-06-06|url-status=live|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180212201830/https://www.ndtv.com/india-news/countrys-biggest-solar-park-at-the-heart-of-indias-clean-energy-push-1696271|archive-date=2018-02-12}}</ref><ref>[https://timesofindia.indiatimes.com/city/jaipur/solar-plants-of-620-mw-get-operational-at-bhadla-park/articleshow/66035558.cms Solar plants of 620 MW get operational at Bhadla park] {{Webarchive|url=https: