  || Founder of Guerrilla Skepticism on Wikipedia discussing ''New York Times'' coverage of psychic sting operation on [[Thomas John Flanagan|Thomas John]]<ref>{{cite web |title=Podcast #713 - March 9th, 2019 |url=https://www.facebook.com/theskepticsguide/posts/10156889859126605 |website=Facebook.com |publisher=SGU Productions |accessdate=29 April 2019}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |title=Podcast #713 - March 9th, 2019 |url=https://www.theskepticsguide.org/podcast/sgu/713 |website=theskepticsguide.org |publisher=SGU Productions |accessdate=29 April 2019}}</ref>\n\n|}\n\n== Recognition ==\n''The Skeptics' Guide'' won the 2009 [[Podcast Awards]] in the \"Education\" category, and the 2010, 2011, 2012, and 2014 Podcast Awards in the \"Science\" category.<ref name=\"PodcastAwards.com\">{{cite web |title=Podcast Award Winners 2005-2014 |url=http://www.podcastawards.com/index.php?option=pastwinners |work=The People's Choice Podcast Awards |accessdate=12 February 2016 |archive-url=https://www.webcitation.org/6Lh9tnIpR?url=http://www.podcastawards.com/index.php?option=pastwinners |archive-date=December 7, 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nIt was also a 2014 \u201cDose of Rationality\u201d Top 10 Podcast,<ref>{{cite web|title=The 2014 \u201cDose of Rationality\u201d Top 10 Podcasts!|publisher=Rationality Unleashed| author=Sacerich, Robert | date=July 9, 2014 |url=http://www.rationalityunleashed.net/2014-dose-rationality-top-10-podcasts/ |accessdate=April 5, 2016 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20151120032416/http://www.rationalityunleashed.net/2014-dose-rationality-top-10-podcasts/ |archivedate=November 20, 2015 }}</ref>\nand a 2010 Physics.org Best Podcast nominee.<ref>{{cite web|title=The physics.org web awards 2010|url=http://www.physics.org/featuredetail.asp?id=52|publisher=Institute of Physics|accessdate=12 February 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151204162736/http://www.physics.org/featuredetail.asp?id=52|archive-date=December 4, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n== Sponsors and membership ==\nOn July 30, 2013, Dr. Steven Novella announced that the SGU would begin offering membership and airing sponsors. Dr. Novella went on to say that the money raised would go into funding skeptical activities, including but not limited to, development of skeptical educational content and web-series such as \"Occ The Skeptical Caveman.\" The addition of sponsors is not permanent, according to Dr. Novella, they shall be removed \"if 4% of listeners support the SGU through membership at an average of the $8 per month level.\"<ref>{{cite web |url= http://theness.com/neurologicablog/index.php/the-sgu-and-skeptical-activism/ |title= The SGU and Skeptical Activism |publisher= Neurologica Blog |accessdate= December 10, 2013 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20131213035847/http://theness.com/neurologicablog/index.php/the-sgu-and-skeptical-activism/ |archive-date= December 13, 2013 |url-status= live }}</ref> \nThough membership has begun, the SGU continues to publish a free weekly sponsored podcast. Membership entitles one to an ad-free version of The SGU, extra content, and discounts to NECSS (The Northeast Conference on Science and Skepticism). Membership range from $4/month to $200/month.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.theskepticsguide.org/member-subscription |title= Member Subscription |publisher= The Skeptics Guide To The Universe |accessdate= December 12, 2013 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20131219191628/http://www.theskepticsguide.org/member-subscription |archive-date= December 19, 2013 |url-status= live }}</ref>\n\nAdditional financial support from listeners is provided through [[Patreon]]. The SGU has established several goals after achieving a certain number of financial supporters.  A major benchmark was reached in 2018 with 3,000 Patreon supporters that sustained enough predictable income for a full-time employee.<ref name=\"TheESP160\" />  Other benchmarks include a 12-hour and 24-hour live show after reaching 4,000 and 5,500 supporters, respectively.[https://www.patreon.com/SkepticsGuide]  These live shows may be located on the most complete and accurate reproduction of the [[Starship Enterprise]] [[Star Trek: The Original Series]] set, which was built by [[James Cawley]] and can be seen on the SGU Patreon page introduction video. <ref name=\"TheESP160\" /> \n\n== SGU 5x5 ==\nA companion podcast, ''The Skeptics' Guide 5x5'' (''SGU 5x5'' for short), described as \"five minutes with five skeptics,\"<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.theness.com/ |title= The NESS |publisher= The New England Skeptical Society |accessdate= January 8, 2010 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20100317124004/http://www.theness.com/ |archive-date= March 17, 2010 |url-status= live }}</ref> consist of single-topic episodes which often delve into specific types of logical [[fallacy]].<ref>{{cite news |title= The Web's Most Illogical Arguments |first= Robert |last= Strohmeyer |url= http://news.idg.no/cw/art.cfm?id=9309FF4D-1A64-67EA-E45DF52DAF5A3A35 |publisher= IDG News Service |work= Computerworld |date= December 15, 2009 |accessdate= January 8, 2010 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20110722110434/http://news.idg.no/cw/art.cfm?id=9309FF4D-1A64-67EA-E45DF52DAF5A3A35 |archive-date= July 22, 2011 |url-status= live }}</ref> SGU 5x5 did not appear regularly and there were no episodes between {{dts|2011|01|26}} and {{dts|2012|02|08}}. There have been no episodes released since {{dts|2012|05|09}}.<ref>{{cite web\n    | url = http://www.theskepticsguide.org/podcast/5x5\n    | title = List of SGU 5x5 podcast episodes\n    | access-date = January 12, 2015\n    | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20150207034928/http://theskepticsguide.org/podcast/5x5\n    | archive-date = February 7, 2015\n    | url-status = live\n    }}</ref>\n\n== ''The Skeptics' Guide to the Universe'' book ==\n{{Main|The Skeptics' Guide to the Universe (book)}}\n''The Skeptics' Guide to the Universe: How to Know What's Really Real in a World Increasingly Full of Fake'' is a 2018 book written by Steven Novella and co-authored by the other current co-hosts of The Skeptics' Guide to the Universe podcast\u2014Bob Novella, Cara Santa Maria, Jay Novella, and Evan Bernstein. It also contains posthumous material from former co-host Perry DeAngelis. The book is meant to be an all-encompassing guide to skeptical thinking.  In an interview with The [[European Skeptics Podcast]], Jay Novella describes their approach to writing the book from the \"point of view of an alien species observing the earth from a skeptical perspective using critical thinking,\" reminiscent of the podcast's namesake [[The Hitchhiker's Guide to the Galaxy]] by [[Douglas Adams]].<ref name=\"TheESP160\" />\n\n== References ==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n== External links ==\n{{wikiquote}}\n{{Commons category|The Skeptics Guide to the Universe}}\n* {{Official website|http://www.theskepticsguide.org|''The Skeptics' Guide to the Universe'' official website}}\n* [http://www.theness.com New England Skeptical Society Homepage]\n* [http://www.sgutranscripts.org ''SGU'' Transcripts]\n* [https://www.patreon.com/SkepticsGuide ''The Skeptics' Guide to the Universe'' Patreon Page]\n\n{{Podcasting}}\n{{Skeptical podcasts}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Skeptics Guide to the Universe, The}}\n[[Category:Audio podcasts]]\n[[Category:Scientific skepticism mass media]]\n[[Category:Science podcasts]]\n[[Category:Talk podcasts]]\n[[Category:2005 podcast debuts]]\n", "text_old": "{{for|the book based on the podcast|The Skeptics' Guide to the Universe (book)}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=March 2020}}\n{{Infobox Podcast\n| title = The Skeptics' Guide to the Universe\n|image = [[Image:Skepticsguideweb.png|250px]]\n| host = Dr. [[Steven Novella]]<br />Jay Novella<br />Bob Novella<br />Evan Bernstein<br />[[Cara Santa Maria]]\n| url = [http://www.theskepticsguide.org www.theskepticsguide.org]\n| status = Weekly\n| began = May 4, 2005\n| ended =\n| genre = [[Science]] and [[scientific skepticism|skepticism]]\n}}\n\n'''''The Skeptics' Guide to the Universe''''' is a weekly 80-minute [[podcast]] hosted by [[Steven Novella]], [[Doctor of Medicine|MD]], along with a panel of \"[[Scientific skepticism|skeptical]] rogues.\"  It is named to evoke [[The Hitchhiker's Guide to the Galaxy]] and is the official podcast of the [[New England Skeptical Society]].  The show features discussions of recent scientific developments [[Wiktionary:in layman's terms|in layman's terms]], and interviews authors, people in the area of science, and other famous skeptics. The show also includes discussions of [[Urban myth|myths]], [[conspiracy theories]], [[pseudoscience]], the [[paranormal]], and many general forms of superstition, from the point of view of [[scientific skepticism]]. [[Steven Novella]], the host of the show, has been particularly active in debunking pseudoscience in medicine. His activities include opposing the claims of [[Vaccine controversy|anti-vaccine activists]], [[homeopathy]] practitioners and individuals [[HIV/AIDS denialism|denying the link between HIV and AIDS]].<ref name=\"pmid18199017\">{{cite journal |author1=Novella S|authorlink1=Steven Novella|author2=Roy R|author3=Marcus D|author4=Bell IR|author5=Davidovitch N|author6=Saine A |title=A debate: homeopathy\u2014quackery or a key to the future of medicine? |journal=J Altern Complement Med |volume=14 |issue=1 |pages=9\u201315 |year= 2008|pmid=18199017 |doi=10.1089/acm.2007.0770}}</ref><ref name=\"pmid18194763\">{{cite journal |author1=Gold PW|author2=Novella S|authorlink2=Steven Novella|author3=Roy R|author4=Marcus D|author5=Bell I|author6=Davidovitch N|author7=Saine A |title=Homeopathy\u2014quackery or a key to the future of medicine? |journal=Homeopathy |volume=97 |issue=1 |pages=28\u201333 |year=2008 |pmid=18194763 |doi=10.1016/j.homp.2007.12.002}}</ref><ref name=\"pmid17713982\">{{cite journal |author1=Smith TC|author2=Novella SP |authorlink2=Steven Novella|title=HIV Denial in the Internet Era |journal=PLoS Med |volume=4 |issue=8 |pages=e256 |year=2007 |pmid=17713982 |doi=10.1371/journal.pmed.0040256 |pmc=1949841}}</ref>\n\n==Hosts==\n===Current hosts===\nAll of the SGU hosts, with the exception of Jay Novella beginning in 2018, maintain careers separate from the podcast.  The SGU contemplated hiring a full-time employee to meet the demands of a growing audience but was hindered due to a [[Steven_Novella#Tobinick_lawsuit|defamation lawsuit]] filed by [[Edward Tobinick]] that consumed financial resources that would have otherwise been available.<ref name=\"TheESP160\">{{cite podcast |url=http://theesp.eu/podcast_archive/theesp_ep_160_jay_novella_the_skeptics_guide_to_the_universe.html |title=TheESP Ep. #160 - Jay Novella & The Skeptics\u2019 Guide to the Universe |website=soundcloud.com |time=1:16:26 |date=4 March 2019 |access-date=22 March 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190323150750/http://theesp.eu/podcast_archive/theesp_ep_160_jay_novella_the_skeptics_guide_to_the_universe.html |archivedate=March 23, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n* '''[[Steven Novella]]'''\n:The principal host of the show. He is an American [[neurology|clinical neurologist]] and [[Professors in the United States#Assistant Professor|assistant professor]] at [[Yale University School of Medicine]].<ref name= physicianprofile>{{cite web|title=Steven Novella, MD|url=https://www.yalemedicine.org/doctors/steven_novella/|publisher=Yale School of Medicine|accessdate=2019-05-03|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190503064315/https://www.yalemedicine.org/doctors/steven_novella/|archive-date=May 3, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>  He is the president of the [[New England Skeptical Society]] (NESS),<ref>{{cite web|title=The Ness About Us|url=http://www.theness.com/index.php/about/|publisher=The New England Skeptical Society|accessdate=10 June 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160210220702/http://www.theness.com/index.php/about/|archive-date=February 10, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> and is the author of the blog ''[[Steven Novella#Internet|NeuroLogica]]''. He is the executive editor for, and a regular contributor to, ''[[Science-Based Medicine]]'', an influential and respected source of information about medical controversies and [[alternative medicine]].<ref name=\"Freedman\">{{cite news|last1=Freedman|first1=David H.|title=The Triumph of New-Age Medicine|url=https://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2011/07/the-triumph-of-new-age-medicine/308554/|accessdate=23 August 2016|work=[[The Atlantic]]|date=July\u2013August 2011|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150510142230/http://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2011/07/the-triumph-of-new-age-medicine/308554/|archive-date=May 10, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"Senapathy\">{{cite news|last=Senapathy|first=Kavin|url=https://www.forbes.com/sites/kavinsenapathy/2016/05/31/why-is-big-naturopathy-afraid-of-this-lone-whistleblower|title=Why Is Big Naturopathy Afraid Of This Lone Whistleblower?|date=2016-05-31|work=Forbes|url-status=live|archive-url=https://archive.today/20200322212737/https://www.forbes.com/sites/kavinsenapathy/2016/05/31/why-is-big-naturopathy-afraid-of-this-lone-whistleblower/%233d54f5de7ee4|archive-date=March 22, 2020|publisher=Forbes Media LLC|location=US|access-date=September 16, 2017}}</ref><ref name=\"Schwarcz\">{{cite news|last1=Joe|first1=Schwarcz|authorlink1=Joseph A. Schwarcz|title=The Right Chemistry: 'Is it safe to kiss your golf balls?'|url=https://montrealgazette.com/technology/science/the-right-chemistry-is-it-safe-to-kiss-your-golf-balls|accessdate=23 August 2016|work=[[Montreal Gazette]]|date=17 July 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190323102259/https://montrealgazette.com/technology/science/the-right-chemistry-is-it-safe-to-kiss-your-golf-balls|archive-date=March 23, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"Gifford\">{{cite news|last1=Gifford|first1=Bill|title=This is What You Get When You Look to TV Stars for Health Advice: Suzanne Somers, Dangerous Medical Hack|url=https://newrepublic.com/article/115574/suzanne-somers-hormone-hackery-unscientific-and-dangerous|work=[[The New Republic]]|date=13 November 2013|accessdate=3 September 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20170517100258/https://newrepublic.com/article/115574/suzanne-somers-hormone-hackery-unscientific-and-dangerous|archive-date=May 17, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref><ref name=\"Moyer\">{{cite news|last1=Moyer|first1=Melinda Wenner|title=Does Fluoride Make Your Kids Dumb?|url=http://www.slate.com/articles/double_x/the_kids/2013/02/does_fluoride_lower_your_child_s_iq_dr_joseph_mercola_says_yes_on_the_huffington.html|accessdate=3 September 2016|work=[[Slate (magazine) |Slate]]|date=11 February 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20171208063351/http://www.slate.com/articles/double_x/the_kids/2013/02/does_fluoride_lower_your_child_s_iq_dr_joseph_mercola_says_yes_on_the_huffington.html|archive-date=December 8, 2017|url-status=live}}</ref>\n* '''Evan Bernstein'''\n* '''[[Cara Santa Maria]]''' (From July 25, 2015)\n* '''Robert \"Bob\" Novella'''\n* '''Jay Novella''' Jay Novella began as a [[software engineer]], which led to a career building layer functionality behind websites and eventually into [[e-commerce]].  He created and maintains the SGU website.  After 13 years with the SGU, he became their first full-time employee in 2018, resulting from reaching a [[Patreon]] target of 3,000 donors.<ref name=\"TheESP160\" /><ref>{{cite podcast |url=https://soundcloud.com/user-721155342/theesp-ep-008-jay-novella |title=TheESP Ep. #008 - Jay Novella by European Skeptics Podcast |website=soundcloud.com |time=11:12 |date=3 February 2016 |access-date=25 January 2019 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20190323041937/https://soundcloud.com/user-721155342/theesp-ep-008-jay-novella |archivedate=March 23, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Palmer |first1=Rob |title=A Conversation with Skeptics\u2019 Guide Rogue Jay Novella (Part 3) |url=https://www.csicop.org/specialarticles/show/a_conversation_with_skeptics_guide_rogue_jay_novella_part_3 |website=Skeptical Inquirer |accessdate=22 February 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190218210103/https://www.csicop.org/specialarticles/show/a_conversation_with_skeptics_guide_rogue_jay_novella_part_3 |archive-date=February 18, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n{{Gallery\n|title=\n|width=120 | height=120\n|align=center\n|File:Steve Novella.jpg|Steve Novella, 2011\n|File:Evan Bernstein 2015.jpg|Evan Bernstein, 2015\n|File:Cara Santa Maria at Skepticon.jpg|Cara Santa Maria, 2014\n|File:The Know Show - Bob Novella with LARP prop.jpg|Bob Novella (right) with prop during a live show, 2019\n|File:Jay Novella.png|Jay Novella, 2015\n}}\n\n===Former hosts===\n* '''[[Perry DeAngelis]]'''\n:On August 19, 2007, co-host DeAngelis died shortly before his 44th birthday after suffering from a number of chronic illnesses (most significantly [[scleroderma]]).<ref>{{cite web | last = Novella | first = Steven | authorlink = Steven Novella | url = http://www.theness.com/neurologicablog/index.php | title = Perry DeAngelis: 8/22/1963 8/19/2007 | work = NeuroLogica Blog | date = 20 August 2007 | accessdate = 8 March 2012 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20071026072357/http://www.theness.com/neurologicablog/index.php | archive-date = October 26, 2007 | url-status = live }}</ref> During the two weeks before his passing, DeAngelis phoned in his contribution to the Skeptical quote segment for which he was responsible at the time from his hospital room.\n* '''[[Rebecca Watson]]''' (From March 29, 2006 to December 27, 2014.)\n:On December 27, 2014, co-host Watson announced that she has recorded her final show prior to leaving the organization.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Watson|first1=Rebecca|authorlink=Rebecca Watson|title=Why I\u2019ve Left SGU|url=http://skepchick.org/2014/12/why-ive-left-sgu/|website=Skepchick.org|publisher=Skepchick|date=27 December 2014|accessdate=27 July 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141227132607/http://skepchick.org/2014/12/why-ive-left-sgu/|archive-date=December 27, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref>\n{{Gallery\n|title=\n|width=120 | height=120\n|align=center\n|File:Perry DeAngelis 2000.jpg|Perry DeAngelis, 2000\n|File:Rebecca watson geek.jpg|Rebecca Watson, 2009\n}}\n\n== Production ==\nThe show is prerecorded via a [[Skype]] conference call. Each caller records their own audio and then the individually recorded tracks are mixed together when Steven Novella edits the show in post-production. British comedian and skeptic [[Iszi Lawrence]] provides voice-over introductions for the show and certain segments. With Jay Novella becoming the first full-time employee with the SGU, his contribution to recording and production will increase, as will his responsibilities to growing the audience of the SGU through marketing, social media, and a newsletter.<ref name=\"TheESP160\" />  Larger projects will be coordinated through him that will provide a more professional appearance in a timely manner that a larger audience demands. \n\n[[File:SGU cast at CSICon 2017 in Las Vegas.jpg|thumb|250px|SGU live recording at CSICon 2017 in Las Vegas. From left to right: Rachael Dunlop (guest), Evan Bernstein, Jay Novella, Steven Novella, Cara Santa Maria, and Bob Novella.]]\n\n=== Segments ===\n; Opening:  The Skeptics' Guide opens with Steven Novella introducing each panelist in attendance, typically leading to the retrospective segment \"This Day in Skepticism\". The panelists then discuss that week's top news stories of concern to skeptics. This is generally followed with answering of listener email.\n\n<!-- \"Whaddyaknow?\" -->\n; \"What's the Word\": Cara Santa Maria presents a technical word, discussing the history and etymology of the word and how it currently applies to various scientific disciplines.\n\n[[File:Live at the Australian Skeptics National Convention 2014.JPG|thumb|250x250px|The SGU at 2014 Australian Skeptics National Convention. From left to right: George Hrab, Evan Bernstein, Rebecca Watson, Steven Novella, Jay Novella, Bob Novella, and Richard Saunders.]]\n\n;\"Forgotten Superheroes of Science\": Bob Novella describes a notable scientific figure from the past who is not well-known, ending with an encouragement to mention the figure to your friends when discussing their obscure area of expertise.\n\n; \"Who's That Noisy?\": A [[Media clip|sound clip]] is played for listeners to guess what, or who it is.  This segment was originally hosted by Bernstein, but is currently hosted by Jay Novella.  The first episode it appeared in was [https://legacy.theskepticsguide.org/podcast/sgu/181 #181].  The name comes from Steven's daughter who, when she was 2 years old, would say \"who's that noisy\" instead of \"what's that noise?\"\n\n; \"A Quickie with Bob\": Any of the rogues (apart from Bob) can ask for 'a quickie with Bob' who will then address an issue of current scientific news. Tends to happen before the interview section in around one minute, to a set length piece of background music.\n\n; Interview: Most weeks the panel interview a guest skeptic or scientist.\n\n; \"Science or Fiction\":  Steven Novella presents the panelists with three recent stories of a scientific nature, one of which is fiction. The co-hosts then have to use their knowledge of science and skeptical senses to figure out which story is fiction. The fake story may either be a complete fabrication or based on a factual story with a critical detail changed to make it fictitious. \"Science or Fiction\" is occasionally themed, such that all stories discuss similar topics.\n\n; \"Skeptical Quote\": The show closes with Jay Novella reading a quote from a famous person that is relevant to skepticism or science. Bob did the first skeptical quote although it wasn't really specific to any one of the rogues. (\"Isaac Asimov. A scientist fiction writer of some note.\") Jay announces the source in an exaggerated radio announcer voice. On May 10, 2008 host Steven Novella  posted a survey on the SGU message board asking listeners if they preferred Jay read the source of the quote before or after the reading of the quote.<ref>{{cite web|author=Novella, Steven|authorlink=Steven Novella|title=Topic: Skeptical Quote Survey|publisher=The Skeptics Guide to the Universe Forum|url=http://sguforums.com/index.php/topic,10521.msg236235.html#msg236235|date=May 10, 2008|accessdate=April 5, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180426213603/https://sguforums.com/index.php/topic,10521.msg236235.html#msg236235|archive-date=April 26, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> The voting is open ended.\n\nOnly since 2010, has the \"Who's That Noisy?\" segment been before the interview; pre-2010, it was just before the \"Skeptical Quote\".\n\nMost podcasts last around 80 minutes but on September 23, 2011 SGU produced a 24-hour-long podcast with contributions by skeptics from around the world. It was referred to as SGU-24.\n\n==== Occasional and defunct segments ====\n; \"Guest Rogue\": Since the start of 2010, sometimes, instead of having an interview, the Skeptic's Guide will invite a \"guest rogue\" to be present throughout the show including the news and \"Science or Fiction\" segments, as if they were one of the cast.\n\n; \"Skeptical Puzzle\": At the end of the show, Evan Bernstein used to present the listeners with a skeptical puzzle, usually about some person or topic within the field of [[pseudoscience]]. Occasionally the puzzle was presented in verse, and on Episode 96 it was presented as if by a fictional skeptical rapper Kom\u2019n Cents.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.theskepticsguide.org/skepticsguide/podcastinfo.asp?pid=96|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20070927204827/http://www.theskepticsguide.org/skepticsguide/podcastinfo.asp?pid=96|url-status=dead|archive-date=2007-09-27|work=Official Skeptics' Guide Site|title=Episode 96}}</ref> Listeners would answer the puzzle via email or on the message board. Recognition (albeit no actual cash prize or gift) was given the following week to the first person to correctly answer the puzzle. The Skeptical puzzle has been discontinued since episode #130 to allow Evan to concentrate on other areas including SGU 5x5, though he has since occasionally offered a logic puzzle in lieu of \"Who's That Noisy?\".\n\n; This Day in History: Until 2015, the first segment after introductions was a description of a historical event of scientific or skeptical importance whose anniversary falls on the date of recording or the date the podcast is released.\n\n; \"Randi Speaks\": As of September 20, 2006, [[James Randi]] joined the podcast providing a pre-recorded commentary segment called \"Randi Speaks\". Randi, a professional magician and skeptic, expounds upon a topic on his mind for that week which may or may not have to do with skeptical matters. The segment disappeared for a period but returned for the August 8, 2007 episode with a different format. Instead of Randi delivering a prepared essay, an SGU host asks Randi a question which Randi then answers and expands upon.\n\n; \"Name That Logical Fallacy\": Steven Novella regularly presents the panelists with a recent argument, usually of a pseudoscientific nature, that has either appeared in recent news or has been submitted by listeners for consideration. The panelists are challenged to point out the flaws in the presented argument, with specific references to any [[informal fallacy|logical fallacies]] employed. The segment debuted during Episode 40 but it is not featured in every show.<ref>{{cite web |url= http://www.theskepticsguide.org/skepticsguide/podcast-042606.html |title= Episode 40 |work= Official Skeptics' Guide web site] |access-date= October 4, 2007 |archive-url= https://web.archive.org/web/20080924184634/http://www.theskepticsguide.org/skepticsguide/podcast-042606.html |archive-date= September 24, 2008 |url-status= dead }}</ref> Many of the fallacies named are taken from the show's \"Top 20 Logical Fallacies\" list.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.theskepticsguide.org/logicalfallacies.asp | work = Official Skeptics' Guide web site] | title = Top 20 Logical Fallacies | last = Novella | first = Steven | authorlink = Steven Novella | 7 =  | access-date = July 15, 2007 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20090126061244/http://theskepticsguide.org/logicalfallacies.asp | archive-date = January 26, 2009 | url-status = dead }}</ref>\n\n; \"Swindlers List\": Starting on May 21, 2011, Jay Novella talks about a particular scam he has discovered or been told about. The first scam featured in this section was Bidsell.com.<ref>The Skeptics' Guide To The Universe - Podcast 305 - 5/18/2011 [http://theskepticsguide.org/archive/podcastinfo.aspx?mid=1&pid=305 Episode Show Notes] {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20121203164746/http://theskepticsguide.org/archive/podcastinfo.aspx?mid=1&pid=305 |date=December 3, 2012 }}</ref>\n\n; \"The Dumbest Thing I Heard All Week\": Steve Novella occasionally recounts a subpar article he read during the past week and explains what is wrong with it.\n\n=== Theme music ===\nThe show's theme music is \"Theorem\" by the San Francisco rock band, Kineto.<ref>{{Cite web |url=http://www.myspace.com/kineto |title=Kineto's Myspace page |access-date=February 25, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130614234205/https://myspace.com/kineto |archive-date=June 14, 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref> The theme was acquired from the [[Podsafe Music Network]]. Prior to the November 2, 2005 show, [[Thomas Dolby]]'s \"[[She Blinded Me with Science]]\" was the show's theme.\n\n== Guests ==\n<!-- In case it's not obvious the list is chronological -->\nMany ''Skeptics' Guide'' episodes contain [[interview]]s. Often the interviews feature well-known scientists or skeptics, for instance [[Massimo Pigliucci]] or [[Joe Nickell]]. Rarely the guests are proponents of [[fringe science|fringe]] or [[pseudoscience|pseudoscientific]] views. Some episodes have guest rogues, such as Bill Nye, participating in the entire podcast. Notable guests include the following:<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.theskepticsguide.org/podcast/sgu | title = Episode list | website = theskepticsguide.org | access-date = June 1, 2014 | archive-url = https://web.archive.org/web/20140527155752/http://www.theskepticsguide.org/podcast/sgu | archive-date = May 27, 2014 | url-status = live }}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable\" \n|-\n! width=\"100\" align=\"left\" scope=\"col\" | Show Date\n! width=\"70\"  align=\"left\" scope=\"col\" data-sort-type=\"number\" | Episode\n! width=\"160\" align=\"left\" scope=\"col\" | Guest\n! width=\"400  align=\"left\" scope=\"col\" class=\"unsortable\" | Description\n|-\n| ''Frequent guest'' || --- || [[James Randi]] || A [[Canadian-American]] [[magician (illusion)|stage magician]] and [[scientific skepticism|scientific skeptic]], founder of the [[James Randi Educational Foundation]]\n|-\n| ''Frequent guest'' || --- || [[Phil Plait]] || An American astronomer and [[skeptic]], former president of the James Randi Educational Foundation, known as \"The Bad Astronomer\"\n|-\n| ''Frequent guest'' || --- || [[George Hrab]] || Musician, skeptic podcaster\n|-\n| ''Frequent guest'' || --- || [[Richard Saunders (skeptic)|Richard Saunders]] || An [[Australia]]n skeptic, [[podcast]]er and professional [[origami]]st<ref name=Archive/>\n|-\n| {{dts|2005|06|29}} || 5 || [[Michael Shermer]] || Founder of [[The Skeptics Society]], author of ''[[Why People Believe Weird Things: Pseudoscience, Superstition, and Other Confusions of Our Time|Why People Believe Weird Things]]'' <ref name=Archive/>\n|-\n|September 7, 2005\n|12\n|[[Steven Milloy|Steve Milloy]]\n|Founder of junkscience.com\n|-\n| {{dts|2005|10|06}} || 15 || [[Chris Mooney (journalist)|Chris Mooney]] || Author of ''[[The Republican War on Science]]''<ref name=Archive/>\n|-\n| {{dts|2006|07|05}} || 50 || [[Gerald Posner]] || Author of ''[[Case Closed (book)|Case Closed]]'' <ref name=Archive/>\n|-\n| {{dts|2006|07|12}} || 51|| [[Neal Adams]] || A proponent of the [[Hollow Earth|hollow]] and [[Expanding earth theory|expanding earth]] hypotheses <ref name=Archive/>\n|-\n| {{dts|2006|10|04}} || 63 || [[Michael Shermer]] || Founder of [[The Skeptics Society]], author of ''[[Why People Believe Weird Things: Pseudoscience, Superstition, and Other Confusions of Our Time|Why People Believe Weird Things]]'' <ref name=Archive/>\n|-\n| {{dts|2006|12|13}} || 73 || [[B. Alan Wallace]] || The president and founder of the Santa Barbara Institute for Consciousness Studies<ref name=Archive/>\n|-\n| {{dts|2007|01|31}} || 80 || [[Teller (magician)|Teller]] || One-half of the [[Magic (illusion)|illusionist]] team [[Penn and Teller]] <ref name=Archive>The Skeptic's Guide to the Universe podcast archive, http://www.theskepticsguide.org/archive/podcast.aspx?mid=1 {{Webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130503122609/http://www.theskepticsguide.org/archive/podcast.aspx?mid=1 |date=May 3, 2013 }}, retrieved 10/04/2012</ref>\n|-\n| {{dts|2007|02|07}} || 81 || [[Adam Savage]] and [[Tory Belleci]] || From the [[Discovery Channel]] show ''[[MythBusters]]'' <ref name=Archive/>\n|-\n| {{dts|2007|02|15}} || 82 || [[Christopher Hitchens]] || Journalist and literary critic, author of ''[[God Is Not Great|God is not Great: How Religion Poisons Everything]]''<ref name=Archive/><ref>{{cite web|last1=Gerbic|first1=Susan|authorlink=Susan Gerbic|title=An Interview with CSICon Speaker Bob Novella|url=https://www.csicop.org/specialarticles/show/an_interview_with_csicon_speaker_bob_novella|website=Skeptical Inquirer|publisher=CSI|accessdate=13 January 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180114073726/https://www.csicop.org/specialarticles/show/an_interview_with_csicon_speaker_bob_novella|archive-date=January 14, 201